name: Maxine Waters
tweet_text: I took to the microphones, & I described my understanding of the anger, the distrust, and the feelings of being trapped with nowhere to go. No jobs, no careers, not enough food, and the constant shadow of hostile police, targeting unarmed young black men in particular, for abuse.

name: Maxine Waters
tweet_text: My description and discussion of the unrest that took place on April 29th, 1992, described the miserable conditions and police abuse that was so prevalent in Los Angeles and in communities of color in particular.

name: Maxine Waters
tweet_text: In the following days, while working on the street, responding to radio calls and telephone interviews, I defined the unrest differently from many outside observers, who claimed the unrest was just a bunch of criminals who wanted to steal and destroy.

name: Maxine Waters
tweet_text: I organized to get food, baby diapers, and medicine to the public housing units in South LA, starting with Nickerson Gardens, Jordan Downs, and Imperial Courts housing projects. I then began to work on getting the lights turned on that had been stopped as a result of the unrest.

name: Maxine Waters
tweet_text: The next day I made my way to the Public Housing developments in LA because I knew that the poor people there would be isolated and separated from grocery stores and other resources.

name: Maxine Waters
tweet_text: Upon arriving in LA on April 29th, the day the insurrection took place, I saw that the streetlights were out, and water was streaming through the streets. The police were everywhere. I got to my home and prepared to deal with the unrest unfolding in the streets.

name: Maxine Waters
tweet_text: I immediately reserved a seat on a plane to Los Angeles. During the plane ride, rumors were being spread, that the plane upon entering LA airspace, was going to be targeted with gunshots as a part of the insurrection that was taking place. The rumors did not prove to be true.

name: Maxine Waters
